Regex and Sequence expressions are implemented. Caching is implemented but untested. Doesn't return a parse tree yet--just checks for match success and returns the length of the match--but it should be pretty straightforward to add.
Gah, who wants to put brackets everywhere, anyway?
Implement OneOf. Add default args to match() for ease of testing. Add advice on breaking up regexes.

Implement AllOf.

Factor up to produce _Compound.
Privatize DummyCache. Muse about faster caches.
Support parsing from not-the-beginning of a string.

Expressions now return parse trees!

parsimonious has gone from being merely a recognizer to being a parser! We now cache entire subtrees rather than just lengths, because otherwise we'd have to continually reconstitute nodes out of the cached ints. This is probably horrible for RAM use, but we'll get to that later. At least we're using __slots__.

* Whip parse() into shape. Now it succeeds only if it matches the entire string.
* Make OneOf, AllOf and Optional always return a node for themselves, whether or not their children succeed.
* Remove `pos` param from parse(). If we're going to have it, we should also have an end_pos arg, and I'm not sure it's worthwhile. Just do the slice beforehand.
* Make unnamed Nodes pretty-print more nicely.
* Break down and put tests into TestCases; things were starting to get shadowed.

Hand-write a first draft of the PEG grammar rules.

They seem to work, though they'll surely change as I write the visitor.

Also...
* Start giving access to the Match object in regex nodes. This is probably a bad idea. I liked having one kind of Node, and it's going to be hard on the RAM, but we'll see if it makes the visitors crazy-easy to write.
* Let Nodes compare themselves to None.
* Turn Grammar into basically a dict with a parse() method.

First round trip works!

We parsed a grammar definition, turned that parse tree into an expression tree, and used that to parse another string. Woohoo!

Also...
* Support backslash escapes and Python-style raw and unicode strings in literals.
* Forget _Container; use _Compound instead. It makes tree traversal easier (when writing visitors). We can bring it back if the extra list dereference turns out to be costly.
* Node.full_text is what `text` was. Now Node.text returns only the matched text. Handy!
* Add nice error handling to NodeVisitor. It points out where in the parse tree it failed.

Bootstrap the parser. Big code dump.

It has succeeded in parsing its grammar description DSL and in visiting that AST to turn it into working Expressions. There are still some bugs to work out; test_grammar:IntegrationTests fails. And we should probably have the parsed grammar reparse the DSL description of the DSL and use *that* as our standard grammar--standard multi-level compiler bootstrap--or else at least have a test assert that that's equivalent to what we have now.

Some other highlights:

* Make node repr more explicit. Now I don't get confused anymore. And if I was getting confused, imagine the poor non-me user.
* Start ExpressionFlattener, which will ultimately turn into round-tripping for Expressions: they'll be able to spit out a DSL representations of themselves.
* Fix and complete lots of stuff surrounding expression-tree visitation and DSL parsing. NodeVisitor no longer implements a default generic_visit, because it's not obvious if there would be a generally useful one. Turn visit_rules around to join the era where NodeVisitor, not the subclasses, take care of the recursion.
* Fix test_optional, which was wrong.
* Pick a decent (though not great) name for the grammar description language. We're calling it the "DSL". Renamed a bunch of symbols in that vein.

Next, see what's breaking test_integration, and fix it. Then, after a few more tests, I'll consider #2 done.

Get rid of the Empty expression.

I don't offhand what this would be useful for, but there's no reason we should have to change a grammar just to toggle between match-to-end and not.

Significantly improve reprs of Expressions and Grammars. Grammar reprs are round-trippable.

Now it's clear not only what an Expression's class is but also what its entire tree is, in terms of the same rule syntax that created it.

Factor up the thing where __str__ is just the encoded __unicode__. Not sure I like this.

Add test for #8: test_unicode_crash. This should have been part of f19557bc6440697b394368c48331dc2af0894676.
After reading Ford's first PEG paper again, I realized there's a good name for the textual representation of expressions: "rules". Switch vocab to match.
Make match() suitable for public use.
Remove _DummyCache. Remove now-unused default args from _uncached_match() methods.
There's no reason to push cache creation all the way up into parse().
Rename _rhs() to _as_rhs() for consistency with as_rule().

Get the & operator right.

It's supposed to be a unary prefix operator. This is clear from Ford 2004, and it's more concise this way anyhow: you can just say "a &b" rather than "ab & a".

Don't bother porting lookaheads to the bootstrapping grammar, since it's not used in the rule DSL.

fix(uiGridHeader): Fix height calculations

Header heights were wrong in the "row header", as well as kinda weird when
multiple filters were on one column and another only had one: the border
on the second one would be too short.

This change adds handling for updating the headers' heights to keep them
consistent. Any header cell shorter than the largest header gets explicitly set to the
right height.

Alternatively every header cell will get set to the "inner" height of its
header so a shorter header cell will still have the right border size as a
larger one.
